snippet.textDisplay:
I find the following paraphrased ideas beneficial for coping with Anxiety and Depression.


Focusing on the past results in depression
Focusing on the present results in peace
Focusing on the future results in anxiety


Don't worry about tomorrow's troubles when you have enough to do today.




Emotions seem permanent when we are experiencing them because emotions are intended to cause action and need to seem to be permanent. Otherwise, what else would stir us toward any action or goal? We know by looking through our own histories that emotions change constantly. Therefore, take heart and know that even though you feel permanently stuck it will subside. It always has and always will. It's just some emotions, environments, or situations that take longer than others to resolve. It always seems impossible until it doesn't. Its the same way with learning a new job or a new concept in school. You think "I'll never get this", but you do.


I greatly encourage anyone suffering from depression or anxiety to find a professional: LPC's or religious leaders (many have formal counseling training). Also, religious leaders are free. If they are not free then you know to keep looking. It's hard to suffer from depression and anxiety.


Your not alone even though it feels like it. That statement is cliche for a reason.


Does anyone have anything else to add?

Student: "Sir, can I ask a question?"

Teacher: "Yes!"

Student: "How do you put an elephant inside a fridge?"

Teacher: "I don't know."

Student: "It's easy, you just open the fridge and put it in. I have another question!"

Teacher: "Ok, ask."

Student: "How to put a donkey inside the fridge?"

Teacher: "It's easy, you just open the fridge and put it in."

Student: "No sir, You just open the fridge take out the elephant and put it in." Teacher: "Ooh...ok!!"

Student: "Let me ask another one. If all the animals went to the lion's birthday party, and one animal went missing which one would it be?"

Teacher: "The lion of course! Because it wud eat all the animals."

Student: "No sir, it is the donkey becoz it's still inside the fridge."

Teacher: "Are you kidding me?"

Student: "No sir, 1 last question."

Teacher: "Ok!"

Student: "If there's a river full of crocodiles and you wanted to cross, how would you?"

Teacher: "There's no way, I would need a boat to cross."

Student: "No sir, you just swim and cross it because all the animals went to the lion's birthday party..."

Teacher: "I have my own question, if all the students come to school except one person, who is the person..."

Student: "No idea sir..."

Teacher: "It's you because you are on two weeks suspension."

snippet.textDisplay:
Been through about 7 therapists, and I dont think race is really the thing we have to focus on, maybe it's just who the therapist is and do we gell well with them, does race play a factor? Oh yes, but culturally sensitive therapists would probably be more of a realistic option, how can you control who pursues a degree and where they practice, you can't, can you try introducing culturally sensitive materials to HELP make that bridge more crossable, yeah. I've had some therapists who I end up resenting for pretty much judging me throughout the process, other's I loved and felt like I COULD open up and make some progress, but the critical thing was, I had to actually go from one therapist to another to notice the difference. Did some actually listen to what I had to say? Yeah, but others were quick to try to diagnose and give me drugs or push for a single "do this and you'll be fine" solution then actually trying to talk through everything I felt I needed to talk about


Not sure how it all fits, but, just felt I needed to give my 2 cents, the entire process is far more complicated then we give it credit for, different people need different things at different times, that also applies to the kind of therapist they may need at the time...so many things make this hard without other people making it worse

One day I had to explain the him that his political and social view work for him and not me because we are not the same person and the politics and social construct he believed in were designed to benefit conservative white males. It was like it blew his mind. He couldn’t wrap his head around the concept that every political and social structure he had put his faith in was designed to benefit him based off of a combination of his skin color and gender. He would proceed to deny that racism exists in the modern day United States, and I would proceed to point out that his own son was brout up on the exact same criminal charges as I was, but instead of receiving 6 months jail time with a years of house arrest and therapy, his charge was, “admonished” from his record under the condition he did 2 months in jail so he could, sit and think,” about what he did wrong, with weekly anger management/anger control therapy classes.
